### Intelligence Layer (Automatic)
CCC auto-adjusts dispatch parameters based on:
- **Task complexity:** "fix typo" → 15 turns/$2, "build SaaS" → 50 turns/$10
- **Project stack:** Reads package.json, Dockerfile, etc. → suggests relevant skills
- **Session history:** Learns success rates per task category
- **Smart retry:** Context overflow → fewer turns, rate limit → wait 60s
No configuration needed — works automatically on every dispatch.

### Dialectic Review (Important Decisions)
For architecture choices or expensive-to-reverse decisions:
spawn FOR agent + AGAINST agent + Referee.

### Verification (MANDATORY before marking done)
- [ ] Feature works end-to-end
- [ ] No type/build errors
- [ ] No console errors
- [ ] Committed with conventional commit message
- [ ] Lessons captured in `tasks/lessons.md`

### Pulse & Activity Updates (MANDATORY)
- **Session start:** Post pulse to Linear/task system — "Starting: [task description]"
- **Every major milestone:** Post progress update — what shipped, what's next
- **Session end:** Post summary — files changed, tests passing, issues closed, cost
- **Weekly:** Post project update to Linear with health status (onTrack/atRisk/offTrack)
- **After shipping:** Update project summary, close issues, capture lessons
- Format: bullet points, stats, links. No prose.

### Operationalize Every Fix
After fixing a bug: write class-level tests, sweep codebase for siblings, update CLAUDE.md.

### Self-Improvement
- After ANY correction: update `tasks/lessons.md` immediately
- Review lessons at session start
- Write rules that prevent the same mistake twice

## Core Principles
- **Simplicity First.** Minimal code, minimal impact.
- **No Laziness.** Root causes only. Senior developer standards.
- **Research Before Build.** Check npm, GitHub, existing libs first.
- **Evals Before Specs.** Define "done" and "broken" before writing code.
- **Check Skills First.** Search `SKILLS-INDEX.md` before building from scratch.
- **Boring Solutions Win.** 100 lines when 100 suffice over 1000 lines with abstractions.

